          "body": "Between the wrath-announcement (vv. 9-11) and the harvest (vv. 14-20), John places the chapter's pastoral hinge (vv. 12-13). To saints facing the beast's pressure, John does not say *fight* or *flee* — he says *here is the perseverance* (*hupomonē*) *of the saints who keep the commandments of God and their faith in Jesus*. Perseverance is the saint's calling under the beast. Then comes the second of Revelation's seven beatitudes: *Blessed are the dead who die in the Lord from now on*. The 'from now on' (*ap' arti*) is striking — at this point in the visionary timeline, with the beast in power, the martyrdom of believers is the path to blessing rather than tragedy. The Spirit affirms it: *yes, that they may rest from their labors, for their deeds follow with them*. The chapter that contains Revelation's harshest threat also contains one of its tenderest comforts."
